{
  "texts": [
    "Andrea I. Luppi, E. Rosas, Pedro A.M. Mediano, David K. Menon, and Emmanuel A. Stamatakis [17] analyze information in the context of the information architecture of the brain.",
    "\"As an illustrative example, consider humans' sources of visual information: the eyes.",
    "Unique information is exempli ed by the peripheral information that is lost when one eye is closed: information that cannot be obtained from the remaining eye.",
    "Redundant information is the information that you still have when closing either eye: it is carried equally by both sources.",
    "This provides robustness: despite losing peripheral vision, you can still see what is in front of you even after losing one eye."
  ]
}